{"title_page": "1998 United States Capitol shooting incident", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox terrorist attack\n|title=1998 U.S. Capitol shooting incident\n|image= \n|caption= \n|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]\n|target=[[United States Capitol]]\n|date={{Start date and age|1998|07|24}}\n|time-begin=3:40 p.m.\n|time-end=3:45 p.m.\n|timezone=[[UTC]]-4\n|type=[[Shooting]]\n|fatalities=2\n|weapons=[[.38 S&W|.38 caliber]] [[Smith & Wesson]] revolver\n|injuries=2 (including the perpetrator)\n|perp=Russell Eugene Weston, Jr.\n|motive = \n}}\n\nThe '''1998 United States Capitol shooting incident''' was an attack on July 24, 1998, which led to the deaths of two [[United States Capitol Police]] officers. Officer [[Jacob Chestnut]] and Detective [[John Gibson (police officer)|John Gibson]] were killed when Russell Eugene Weston, Jr., entered the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]] and opened fire.<ref name=CNN>{{cite news | url = http://www.cnn.com/US/9807/24/dc.shooting.03/ | title = 2 dead, 2 hurt in U.S. Capitol shooting | publisher = CNN.com | accessdate = January 19, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061029233005/http://www.cnn.com/US/9807/24/dc.shooting.03/ |archivedate = October 29, 2006}}</ref> Chestnut was killed instantly and Gibson died during surgery at [[George Washington University Hospital]]. Weston's exact motives are unknown, but he has a [[mental disorder]] and maintains a strong distrust of the [[Federal Government of the United States|federal government of the United States]]. He remains in a mental institution due to [[paranoid schizophrenia]] and has yet to be tried in court.\n\n==Shooting==\nOn the day of the shooting, Officer Chestnut and an unarmed, civilian security aide were assigned to operate the X-ray machine and magnetometer at the Document Door entrance located on the East Front of the Capitol, which was open only to [[Member of Congress|Members of Congress]] and their staff. Detective Gibson was assigned to the dignitary protection detail of Rep. Tom DeLay (R-TX) and was in his suite of offices near this door. Weston, armed with a [[.38 S&W|.38 caliber]] [[Smith & Wesson]] six-shot revolver, entered the Document Door at 3:40&nbsp;p.m. At the same time, Officer Chestnut was providing directions to a tourist and his son.<ref name=buried/> Weston walked through the [[metal detector]],  causing the alarm to go off. Chestnut requested he go back through the detector.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/stories/main072598.htm | title = Gunman Shoots His Way Into Capitol; Two Officers Killed, Suspect Captured | publisher = Washingtonpost.com | accessdate = January 12, 2007 | date=January 30, 1999}}</ref> Weston suddenly produced the gun and without warning, shot Chestnut in the back of the head at point-blank range.  At this time, Officer Douglas McMillan, normally working outside the Capitol, was nearby retrieving keys to get a wheelchair for a tourist. As Weston shot Officer Chestnut, Officer McMillan immediately returned fire, causing Weston to shoot toward McMillan. Weston then ran away from McMillan, turning into the first nearby open door that he found. Unfortunately, Officer McMillan was unable to successfully hit Weston, due to the many civilians in the immediate area.  According to witnesses, Weston turned down a short corridor and pushed through a door which leads to a group of offices used by senior Republican representatives including then [[Party whips of the United States House of Representatives|Majority Whip]] [[Tom DeLay]] and Representative [[Dennis Hastert]], future [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] and a close [[Mentorship|prot\u00e9g\u00e9]] of then [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]] [[Newt Gingrich]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.emergency.com/capshoot.htm | title = Attack on Capitol Hill | publisher = EmergencyNet News | accessdate = January 11, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061208155832/http://emergency.com/capshoot.htm |archivedate = December 8, 2006}}</ref>\n\nUpon hearing the gunfire, Detective Gibson, who was in plainclothes, told the office staff to hide under their desks. Within seconds, Gibson was shot after the suspect entered DeLay's office. Despite being mortally wounded, Detective Gibson was able to return fire,  and wound the suspect hitting him with 4 rounds, severely wounding him and causing him to be apprehended in that office by Officer Vincent Farri and Sergeant John Planchart.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/25/us/capitol-hill-slayings-the-overview-gunman-invades-capitol-killing-2-guards.html | title = Capitol Hill Slayings: The Overview; Gunman Invades Capitol, Killing 2 Guards | publisher = Newyorktimes.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 | first=Francis X. | last=Clines | date=July 25, 1998}}</ref> A female tourist was grazed by shrapnel on her face and shoulder, from a marble wall, as Officer McMillan's rounds impacted on the wall, while he was attempting to hit the fleeing Weston.<ref>[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4196/is_19980726/ai_n10434376 \"Horrifying Capitol ordeal began with officer's execution\"]. (July 26, 1998). Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, The.</ref> She was treated for her injuries and released.<ref name=\"Yehle 1, 18\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Yehle |title= Weston Competency Hearing Set |format= |work= Roll Call |publisher= Roll Call, Inc. |location= Washington, D.C. |id= |pages= 1, 18 |date= April 16, 2008 }}</ref> Future Senate Majority Leader [[Bill Frist]], R-Tennessee, a heart surgeon who had been presiding on the Senate floor just before the shooting, resuscitated the gunman and accompanied him to [[D.C. General Hospital]].<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n==After the shooting==\n[[File:Capitol Police Honor Guard - 1998 shooting.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|A Capitol Police Honor Guard salutes the coffins of Officer Jacob Chestnut and Detective John Gibson in the Capitol Rotunda as they lie in repose]]\n\nOfficers Chestnut and Gibson were the two people killed in the attack. Following the shooting, both officers received the tribute of [[lying in honor]] in the [[United States Capitol rotunda]]. They were the first police officers, and Chestnut was the first male [[African American]], to receive the honor.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c105:H.R.4347: | title = Authorizing the use of the Rotunda of the Capitol... | publisher = United States Senate}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Weston was found incompetent to stand trial due to mental illness as he was a man with [[schizophrenia]] who stopped taking his medication.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/04/22/capitol.shooting/ | title = Weston found incompetent to stand trial for Capitol shooting | publisher = CNN.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 | first=Terry | last=Frieden}}</ref> A judge of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]] ordered that he be treated with [[antipsychotic drugs|antipsychotic medication]] without his consent in 2001, and the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] upheld the decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypress.com/14/29/news&columns/feature.cfm |title=Capitol Shooter Russell Weston, Three Years Later |publisher=New York Press |accessdate=January 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128114804/http://www.nypress.com/14/29/news%26columns/feature.cfm |archivedate=November 28, 2006 }}</ref> In 2004, the court determined that Weston still was not competent to be tried, despite ongoing treatment, and suspended but did not dismiss the [[Criminal law|criminal]] charges against him. Weston was known to the [[United States Secret Service]] prior to the incident as a person who had threatened the President of the United States.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.cnn.com/US/9807/24/dc.shooting.04/ | title = Capitol shooting suspect was 'low-level threat' to Clinton | publisher = CNN.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050913025541/http://www.cnn.com/US/9807/24/dc.shooting.04/ |archivedate = September 13, 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe shooting led to the creation of the United States Capitol Police Memorial Fund, a nonprofit organization managed by the [[Capitol Police Board]] which provides funds for the families of Chestnut and Gibson.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/02/1953- | title= U.S. Code Title 2, 1953 | publisher= Cornell Law School | accessdate= January 17, 2007}}</ref> In November 2005, the fund was expanded to include the family of Sgt. Christopher Eney, a USCP officer killed during a training accident in 1984.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/list/press/az01_renzi/flagfootball.html | title = Members, Capitol Police Square Off in 2006 \"Longest Yard\" Flag Football Game | publisher = Rep. Rick Renzi (AZ-01) | accessdate = January 17, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070105104537/http://www.house.gov/list/press/az01_renzi/flagfootball.html |archivedate = January 5, 2007}}</ref> The shooting was cited as one reason for the development of the [[United States Capitol Visitor Center|Capitol Visitors Center]]. The legislation authorizing the construction of the facility was introduced by [[Washington, D.C.]] [[Delegate (United States Congress)|Delegate]] [[Eleanor Holmes Norton]] and was entitled the ''Jacob Joseph Chestnut-John Michael Gibson United States Capitol Visitor Center Act of 1998''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c105:H.R.4347: | title = Jacob Joseph Chestnut-John Michael Gibson United States Capitol Visitor Center Act of 1998 (Introduced in House)\n | publisher = United States House of Representatives | accessdate = January 11, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/stories/security072698.htm | title = Attack Stirs Interest in Visitors Center | publisher = Washingtonpost.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 | date=January 30, 1999}}</ref> The door where Weston entered was renamed in honor of the two officers, from the Document Door to the Chestnut-Gibson Memorial Door.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c105:S.+Con.+Res.+113: | title = To rename the Document Door of the Capitol as the Chestnut-Gibson Memorial Door. (Introduced in Senate) | publisher = United States Senate | accessdate = January 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2008, Weston filed a motion requesting a hearing on his mental status. The hearing was held on May 6 with Weston appearing via teleconference from the [[Federal Correctional Complex, Butner|Federal Medical Center, Butner]] with his public defender Jane Pierce and two witnesses he selected, a psychologist and vocational rehabilitation specialist.<ref>{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Yehle |title= Weston unlikely to ever be tried |format= |work= Roll Call |publisher= Roll Call, Inc. |location= Washington, D.C. |id= |pages= 1, 16 |date= May 7, 2008 }}</ref> Federal judge Earl Britt denied Weston's request to be released from the federal facility, arguing that he failed to present enough evidence that he no longer needed to be committed. During the hearing defense psychologist Holly Rogers stated that, \"sometimes there are individuals who simply do not respond to medication\", implying that Weston was not ready for release. Had Weston been released from the facility, it would have made it possible for him to be taken to Washington, D.C. to stand trial for the murders of Gibson and Chestnut.<ref name=\"Yehle 1, 18\"/>\n\n==Officers==\n{{Main|Jacob Chestnut|John Gibson (police officer)}}\n[[File:Officer Jacob Chestnut, USCP.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Officer Jacob Chestnut, [[United States Capitol Police|USCP]]]]\n[[Image:Detective John Gibson, USCP.jpg|thumb|upright|Detective John Gibson, USCP]]\n\nOfficer '''Jacob Joseph Chestnut''' (April 28, 1940 \u2013 July 24, 1998), was the first [[African American]] to [[lying in honor|lie in honor]] at the Capitol. Chestnut, a retired United States Air Force veteran, is buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]]. His funeral included a speech by President [[Bill Clinton]] and a fly-over by military jets in a [[missing man formation]]. A United States Post Office located in [[Fort Washington, Maryland]] has been renamed in his and Detective John Gibson's honor.<ref name=buried/>\n\n[[Detective]] '''John Michael Gibson''' (March 29, 1956 \u2013 July 24, 1998) was a United States Capitol Police officer assigned to the dignitary protection detail of Congressman Tom DeLay. He is buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]] after [[lying in honor]] with Chestnut in the Capitol rotunda. Detective Gibson had served with the agency for 18 years. He was a native of [[Massachusetts]] who married the niece of Representative [[Joe Moakley]], Democrat of Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/27/us/capitol-hill-slayings-the-police-congress-to-pay-tribute-to-slain-officers.html | title = Capitol Hill slayings: The Police; Congress to Pay Tribute to Slain Officers | publisher = Newyorktimes.com| accessdate = January 17, 2007 | first=Eric | last=Schmitt | date=July 27, 1998}}</ref> He had three children, a 17-year-old daughter and two boys, ages 15 and 14.<ref name=buried>{{cite web | url = http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/gib-ches.htm | title = Capitol Police Officers laid to rest in Arlington National Cemetery | publisher = Michael Robert Patterson | accessdate = January 11, 2007}}</ref>\nGrowing up in New England, Det. Gibson was a lifelong [[Boston Red Sox]] fan, and on August 11, 1998, his beloved team had a moment of silence in his honor prior to a game with the [[Kansas City Royals]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Suspect==\n'''Russell Eugene Weston, Jr.''' (born December 28, 1956), also known as Rusty, grew up in [[Valmeyer, Illinois|Valmeyer]], [[Illinois]]. Weston attended Valmeyer High School, the only high school in a town of 900 people. Shortly after graduating from high school in 1974, Weston moved to [[Rimini, Montana]], rarely returning to Valmeyer. The only attempt his high school classmates made at inviting him to a class reunion was returned with obscenities written across it.<ref name=hospitalized>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/26/us/capitol-hill-slayings-the-suspect-man-hospitalized-in-96-for-ominous-letters.html | title = Capitol Hill Slayings: The Suspect; Man Hospitalized in '96 for Ominous Letters | publisher = Newyorktimes.com | accessdate = January 19, 2007 | date=July 26, 1998}}</ref> Many of Weston's Montana neighbors had disliked him, and often ignored him. They considered him to be unusual, and sometimes [[Eccentricity (behavior)|eccentric]]. Weston had once thought that his neighbor was using his [[television]] [[satellite dish]] to spy on his actions and believed Navy SEALs were hiding in his cornfield.<ref name=hospitalized/>\n\n[[Image:Russellwestonhome.jpg|thumb|left|Weston's cabin next to the lower [[Tenmile Creek (Lewis and Clark County, Montana)|Tenmile Creek]] in [[Montana]] following a search by the police]]\n\nHe was diagnosed with [[Schizophrenia|paranoid schizophrenia]] six years before the shooting and spent fifty-three days in a mental hospital after threatening a Montana resident. He was released after testing as being of no danger to himself or anyone else.<ref name=access/> Eighteen months before the shooting, he moved back to Valmeyer from Montana. Once home, he was known to compulsively hack at trees which filled his back yard following the [[Great Flood of 1993|Mississippi River floods of 1993]]. There was so much downed timber on his family's homestead that they had to ask him to stop cutting at trees.<ref name=access>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/stories/weston081098.htm | title = Before the Shootings, a String of Excesses | publisher = Washingtonpost.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 | date=January 30, 1999}}</ref> Two days prior to the Capitol shooting, at his grandmother's insistence to do something about nearby [[cat]]s which were becoming a nuisance, Weston shot and killed 14 cats with a single-barreled shotgun, leaving several in a bucket and burying the rest.<ref name=access/>\n\nFollowing the Capitol shooting, Weston was transferred to a psychiatric center at [[Butner Federal Correctional Institution]] in [[Butner, North Carolina]]. In an interview with a court-appointed psychiatrist he explained that he stormed the Capitol to prevent the United States from being annihilated by disease and legions of cannibals.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/stories/weston042399.htm | title = Capitol Shooter's Mind-Set Detailed | publisher = Washingtonpost.com | accessdate = January 26, 2010 | date=April 23, 1999}}</ref>\n\nHe has never been charged with any crime due to apparent mental [[culpability|inculpability]]. One contentious issue of Weston's incarceration is that of forced medication. Weston has thus far refused to take any medications voluntarily. His lawyers helped enable this, in order to protect him from the death penalty.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/03/03/opinion/insanity-goes-back-on-trial.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=Sally | last=Satel | title=Insanity Goes Back on Trial | date=March 3, 2003}}</ref> In May 2001, a federal judge authorized doctors to treat Weston involuntarily. A panel from a federal appeals court ruled in July 2001 that Weston could be forced to take the drugs which he was forced to do for 120 days.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F07E5DE153BF930A3575BC0A9649C8B63 | title = Judge Rules Capitol Gunman Can Be Forced to Take Medicine | publisher = Newyorktimes.com | accessdate = January 19, 2007 | date=August 3, 2002}}</ref> He remains in the Butner facility indefinitely.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1954 United States Capitol shooting incident]]\n* [[2013 United States Capitol shooting incident]]\n* [[2017 Congressional baseball shooting]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://projects.ldc.upenn.edu/TDT2000/topics/completed-research/weston-indictment.html Indictment of Russell Eugene Weston, Jr.]\n* [https://archive.is/20130414123326/http://www.c-spanarchives.org/congress/?q=node/77532&id=284650 Tributes by members of Congress], [[C-SPAN]]\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/archives2.htm \"From the Shootings to the Investigation\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Claude Pepper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Persons who have [[lying in state|lain in state or honor]]<br />in the [[United States Capitol rotunda]]<br />(John Gibson and Jacob Chestnut)|years=June 28, 1998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ronald Reagan]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:1998 murders in the United States|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:1998 mass shootings in the United States|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:1998 in American politics|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:1998 in Washington, D.C.|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:Murder in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:United States Capitol Police]]\n[[Category:Attacks on legislatures|United States]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 1998|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:July 1998 events in the United States|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox terrorist attack\n|title=1998 U.S. Capitol shooting incident\n|image= \n|caption= \n|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]\n|target=[[United States Capitol]]\n|date={{Start date and age|1998|07|24}}\n|time-begin=3:40 p.m.\n|time-end=3:45 p.m.\n|timezone=[[UTC]]-4\n|type=[[Shooting]]\n|fatalities=2\n|weapons=[[.38 S&W|.38 caliber]] [[Smith & Wesson]] revolver\n|injuries=2 (including the perpetrator)\n|perp=Russell Eugene Weston, Jr.\n|motive = \n}}\n\nThe '''1998 United States Capitol shooting incident''' was an attack on July 24, 1998, which led to the deaths of two [[United States Capitol Police]] officers. Officer [[Jacob Chestnut]] and Detective [[John Gibson (police officer)|John Gibson]] were killed when Russell Eugene Weston, Jr., entered the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]] and opened fire.<ref name=CNN>{{cite news | url = http://www.cnn.com/US/9807/24/dc.shooting.03/ | title = 2 dead, 2 hurt in U.S. Capitol shooting | publisher = CNN.com | accessdate = January 19, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061029233005/http://www.cnn.com/US/9807/24/dc.shooting.03/ |archivedate = October 29, 2006}}</ref> Chestnut was killed instantly and Gibson died during surgery at [[George Washington University Hospital]]. Weston's exact motives are unknown, but he has a [[mental disorder]] and maintains a strong distrust of the [[Federal Government of the United States|federal government]]. He remains in a mental institution due to [[paranoid schizophrenia]] and has yet to be tried in court.\n\n==Shooting==\nOn the day of the shooting, Officer Chestnut and an unarmed, civilian security aide were assigned to operate the X-ray machine and magnetometer at the Document Door entrance located on the East Front of the Capitol, which was open only to [[Member of Congress|Members of Congress]] and their staff. Detective Gibson was assigned to the dignitary protection detail of Rep. Tom DeLay (R-TX) and was in his suite of offices near this door. Weston, armed with a [[.38 S&W|.38 caliber]] [[Smith & Wesson]] six-shot revolver, entered the Document Door at 3:40&nbsp;p.m. At the same time, Officer Chestnut was providing directions to a tourist and his son.<ref name=buried/> Weston walked through the [[metal detector]],  causing the alarm to go off. Chestnut requested he go back through the detector.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/stories/main072598.htm | title = Gunman Shoots His Way Into Capitol; Two Officers Killed, Suspect Captured | publisher = Washingtonpost.com | accessdate = January 12, 2007 | date=January 30, 1999}}</ref> Weston suddenly produced the gun and without warning, shot Chestnut in the back of the head at point-blank range.  At this time, Officer Douglas McMillan, normally working outside the Capitol, was nearby retrieving keys to get a wheelchair for a tourist. As Weston shot Officer Chestnut, Officer McMillan immediately returned fire, causing Weston to shoot toward McMillan. Weston then ran away from McMillan, turning into the first nearby open door that he found. Unfortunately, Officer McMillan was unable to successfully hit Weston, due to the many civilians in the immediate area.  According to witnesses, Weston turned down a short corridor and pushed through a door which leads to a group of offices used by senior Republican representatives including then [[Party whips of the United States House of Representatives|Majority Whip]] [[Tom DeLay]] and Representative [[Dennis Hastert]], future [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] and a close [[Mentorship|prot\u00e9g\u00e9]] of then [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]] [[Newt Gingrich]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.emergency.com/capshoot.htm | title = Attack on Capitol Hill | publisher = EmergencyNet News | accessdate = January 11, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061208155832/http://emergency.com/capshoot.htm |archivedate = December 8, 2006}}</ref>\n\nUpon hearing the gunfire, Detective Gibson, who was in plainclothes, told the office staff to hide under their desks. Within seconds, Gibson was shot after the suspect entered DeLay's office. Despite being mortally wounded, Detective Gibson was able to return fire,  and wound the suspect hitting him with 4 rounds, severely wounding him and causing him to be apprehended in that office by Officer Vincent Farri and Sergeant John Planchart.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/25/us/capitol-hill-slayings-the-overview-gunman-invades-capitol-killing-2-guards.html | title = Capitol Hill Slayings: The Overview; Gunman Invades Capitol, Killing 2 Guards | publisher = Newyorktimes.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 | first=Francis X. | last=Clines | date=July 25, 1998}}</ref> A female tourist was grazed by shrapnel on her face and shoulder, from a marble wall, as Officer McMillan's rounds impacted on the wall, while he was attempting to hit the fleeing Weston.<ref>[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4196/is_19980726/ai_n10434376 \"Horrifying Capitol ordeal began with officer's execution\"]. (July 26, 1998). Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, The.</ref> She was treated for her injuries and released.<ref name=\"Yehle 1, 18\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Yehle |title= Weston Competency Hearing Set |format= |work= Roll Call |publisher= Roll Call, Inc. |location= Washington, D.C. |id= |pages= 1, 18 |date= April 16, 2008 }}</ref> Future Senate Majority Leader [[Bill Frist]], R-Tennessee, a heart surgeon who had been presiding on the Senate floor just before the shooting, resuscitated the gunman and accompanied him to [[D.C. General Hospital]].<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n==After the shooting==\n[[File:Capitol Police Honor Guard - 1998 shooting.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|A Capitol Police Honor Guard salutes the coffins of Officer Jacob Chestnut and Detective John Gibson in the Capitol Rotunda as they lie in repose]]\n\nOfficers Chestnut and Gibson were the two people killed in the attack. Following the shooting, both officers received the tribute of [[lying in honor]] in the [[United States Capitol rotunda]]. They were the first police officers, and Chestnut was the first male [[African American]], to receive the honor.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c105:H.R.4347: | title = Authorizing the use of the Rotunda of the Capitol... | publisher = United States Senate}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Weston was found incompetent to stand trial due to mental illness as he was a man with [[schizophrenia]] who stopped taking his medication.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/04/22/capitol.shooting/ | title = Weston found incompetent to stand trial for Capitol shooting | publisher = CNN.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 | first=Terry | last=Frieden}}</ref> A judge of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]] ordered that he be treated with [[antipsychotic drugs|antipsychotic medication]] without his consent in 2001, and the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] upheld the decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypress.com/14/29/news&columns/feature.cfm |title=Capitol Shooter Russell Weston, Three Years Later |publisher=New York Press |accessdate=January 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128114804/http://www.nypress.com/14/29/news%26columns/feature.cfm |archivedate=November 28, 2006 }}</ref> In 2004, the court determined that Weston still was not competent to be tried, despite ongoing treatment, and suspended but did not dismiss the [[Criminal law|criminal]] charges against him. Weston was known to the [[United States Secret Service]] prior to the incident as a person who had threatened the President of the United States.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.cnn.com/US/9807/24/dc.shooting.04/ | title = Capitol shooting suspect was 'low-level threat' to Clinton | publisher = CNN.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050913025541/http://www.cnn.com/US/9807/24/dc.shooting.04/ |archivedate = September 13, 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe shooting led to the creation of the United States Capitol Police Memorial Fund, a nonprofit organization managed by the [[Capitol Police Board]] which provides funds for the families of Chestnut and Gibson.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/02/1953- | title= U.S. Code Title 2, 1953 | publisher= Cornell Law School | accessdate= January 17, 2007}}</ref> In November 2005, the fund was expanded to include the family of Sgt. Christopher Eney, a USCP officer killed during a training accident in 1984.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/list/press/az01_renzi/flagfootball.html | title = Members, Capitol Police Square Off in 2006 \"Longest Yard\" Flag Football Game | publisher = Rep. Rick Renzi (AZ-01) | accessdate = January 17, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070105104537/http://www.house.gov/list/press/az01_renzi/flagfootball.html |archivedate = January 5, 2007}}</ref> The shooting was cited as one reason for the development of the [[United States Capitol Visitor Center|Capitol Visitors Center]]. The legislation authorizing the construction of the facility was introduced by [[Washington, D.C.]] [[Delegate (United States Congress)|Delegate]] [[Eleanor Holmes Norton]] and was entitled the ''Jacob Joseph Chestnut-John Michael Gibson United States Capitol Visitor Center Act of 1998''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c105:H.R.4347: | title = Jacob Joseph Chestnut-John Michael Gibson United States Capitol Visitor Center Act of 1998 (Introduced in House)\n | publisher = United States House of Representatives | accessdate = January 11, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/stories/security072698.htm | title = Attack Stirs Interest in Visitors Center | publisher = Washingtonpost.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 | date=January 30, 1999}}</ref> The door where Weston entered was renamed in honor of the two officers, from the Document Door to the Chestnut-Gibson Memorial Door.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c105:S.+Con.+Res.+113: | title = To rename the Document Door of the Capitol as the Chestnut-Gibson Memorial Door. (Introduced in Senate) | publisher = United States Senate | accessdate = January 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2008, Weston filed a motion requesting a hearing on his mental status. The hearing was held on May 6 with Weston appearing via teleconference from the [[Federal Correctional Complex, Butner|Federal Medical Center, Butner]] with his public defender Jane Pierce and two witnesses he selected, a psychologist and vocational rehabilitation specialist.<ref>{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Yehle |title= Weston unlikely to ever be tried |format= |work= Roll Call |publisher= Roll Call, Inc. |location= Washington, D.C. |id= |pages= 1, 16 |date= May 7, 2008 }}</ref> Federal judge Earl Britt denied Weston's request to be released from the federal facility, arguing that he failed to present enough evidence that he no longer needed to be committed. During the hearing defense psychologist Holly Rogers stated that, \"sometimes there are individuals who simply do not respond to medication\", implying that Weston was not ready for release. Had Weston been released from the facility, it would have made it possible for him to be taken to Washington, D.C. to stand trial for the murders of Gibson and Chestnut.<ref name=\"Yehle 1, 18\"/>\n\n==Officers==\n{{Main|Jacob Chestnut|John Gibson (police officer)}}\n[[File:Officer Jacob Chestnut, USCP.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Officer Jacob Chestnut, [[United States Capitol Police|USCP]]]]\n[[Image:Detective John Gibson, USCP.jpg|thumb|upright|Detective John Gibson, USCP]]\n\nOfficer '''Jacob Joseph Chestnut''' (April 28, 1940 \u2013 July 24, 1998), was the first [[African American]] to [[lying in honor|lie in honor]] at the Capitol. Chestnut, a retired United States Air Force veteran, is buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]]. His funeral included a speech by President [[Bill Clinton]] and a fly-over by military jets in a [[missing man formation]]. A United States Post Office located in [[Fort Washington, Maryland]] has been renamed in his and Detective John Gibson's honor.<ref name=buried/>\n\n[[Detective]] '''John Michael Gibson''' (March 29, 1956 \u2013 July 24, 1998) was a United States Capitol Police officer assigned to the dignitary protection detail of Congressman Tom DeLay. He is buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]] after [[lying in honor]] with Chestnut in the Capitol rotunda. Detective Gibson had served with the agency for 18 years. He was a native of [[Massachusetts]] who married the niece of Representative [[Joe Moakley]], Democrat of Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/27/us/capitol-hill-slayings-the-police-congress-to-pay-tribute-to-slain-officers.html | title = Capitol Hill slayings: The Police; Congress to Pay Tribute to Slain Officers | publisher = Newyorktimes.com| accessdate = January 17, 2007 | first=Eric | last=Schmitt | date=July 27, 1998}}</ref> He had three children, a 17-year-old daughter and two boys, ages 15 and 14.<ref name=buried>{{cite web | url = http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/gib-ches.htm | title = Capitol Police Officers laid to rest in Arlington National Cemetery | publisher = Michael Robert Patterson | accessdate = January 11, 2007}}</ref>\nGrowing up in New England, Det. Gibson was a lifelong [[Boston Red Sox]] fan, and on August 11, 1998, his beloved team had a moment of silence in his honor prior to a game with the [[Kansas City Royals]].{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Suspect==\n'''Russell Eugene Weston, Jr.''' (born December 28, 1956), also known as Rusty, grew up in [[Valmeyer, Illinois|Valmeyer]], [[Illinois]]. Weston attended Valmeyer High School, the only high school in a town of 900 people. Shortly after graduating from high school in 1974, Weston moved to [[Rimini, Montana]], rarely returning to Valmeyer. The only attempt his high school classmates made at inviting him to a class reunion was returned with obscenities written across it.<ref name=hospitalized>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/26/us/capitol-hill-slayings-the-suspect-man-hospitalized-in-96-for-ominous-letters.html | title = Capitol Hill Slayings: The Suspect; Man Hospitalized in '96 for Ominous Letters | publisher = Newyorktimes.com | accessdate = January 19, 2007 | date=July 26, 1998}}</ref> Many of Weston's Montana neighbors had disliked him, and often ignored him. They considered him to be unusual, and sometimes [[Eccentricity (behavior)|eccentric]]. Weston had once thought that his neighbor was using his [[television]] [[satellite dish]] to spy on his actions and believed Navy SEALs were hiding in his cornfield.<ref name=hospitalized/>\n\n[[Image:Russellwestonhome.jpg|thumb|left|Weston's cabin next to the lower [[Tenmile Creek (Lewis and Clark County, Montana)|Tenmile Creek]] in [[Montana]] following a search by the police]]\n\nHe was diagnosed with [[Schizophrenia|paranoid schizophrenia]] six years before the shooting and spent fifty-three days in a mental hospital after threatening a Montana resident. He was released after testing as being of no danger to himself or anyone else.<ref name=access/> Eighteen months before the shooting, he moved back to Valmeyer from Montana. Once home, he was known to compulsively hack at trees which filled his back yard following the [[Great Flood of 1993|Mississippi River floods of 1993]]. There was so much downed timber on his family's homestead that they had to ask him to stop cutting at trees.<ref name=access>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/stories/weston081098.htm | title = Before the Shootings, a String of Excesses | publisher = Washingtonpost.com | accessdate = January 11, 2007 | date=January 30, 1999}}</ref> Two days prior to the Capitol shooting, at his grandmother's insistence to do something about nearby [[cat]]s which were becoming a nuisance, Weston shot and killed 14 cats with a single-barreled shotgun, leaving several in a bucket and burying the rest.<ref name=access/>\n\nFollowing the Capitol shooting, Weston was transferred to a psychiatric center at [[Butner Federal Correctional Institution]] in [[Butner, North Carolina]]. In an interview with a court-appointed psychiatrist he explained that he stormed the Capitol to prevent the United States from being annihilated by disease and legions of cannibals.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/stories/weston042399.htm | title = Capitol Shooter's Mind-Set Detailed | publisher = Washingtonpost.com | accessdate = January 26, 2010 | date=April 23, 1999}}</ref>\n\nHe has never been charged with any crime due to apparent mental [[culpability|inculpability]]. One contentious issue of Weston's incarceration is that of forced medication. Weston has thus far refused to take any medications voluntarily. His lawyers helped enable this, in order to protect him from the death penalty.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/03/03/opinion/insanity-goes-back-on-trial.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=Sally | last=Satel | title=Insanity Goes Back on Trial | date=March 3, 2003}}</ref> In May 2001, a federal judge authorized doctors to treat Weston involuntarily. A panel from a federal appeals court ruled in July 2001 that Weston could be forced to take the drugs which he was forced to do for 120 days.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F07E5DE153BF930A3575BC0A9649C8B63 | title = Judge Rules Capitol Gunman Can Be Forced to Take Medicine | publisher = Newyorktimes.com | accessdate = January 19, 2007 | date=August 3, 2002}}</ref> He remains in the Butner facility indefinitely.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1954 United States Capitol shooting incident]]\n* [[2013 United States Capitol shooting incident]]\n* [[2017 Congressional baseball shooting]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://projects.ldc.upenn.edu/TDT2000/topics/completed-research/weston-indictment.html Indictment of Russell Eugene Weston, Jr.]\n* [https://archive.is/20130414123326/http://www.c-spanarchives.org/congress/?q=node/77532&id=284650 Tributes by members of Congress], [[C-SPAN]]\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/shooting/archives2.htm \"From the Shootings to the Investigation\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Claude Pepper]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Persons who have [[lying in state|lain in state or honor]]<br />in the [[United States Capitol rotunda]]<br />(John Gibson and Jacob Chestnut)|years=June 28, 1998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ronald Reagan]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:1998 murders in the United States|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:1998 mass shootings in the United States|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:1998 in American politics|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:1998 in Washington, D.C.|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:Murder in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:United States Capitol Police]]\n[[Category:Attacks on legislatures|United States]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 1998|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:July 1998 events in the United States|United States Capitol Shooting]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Washington,